## Engineering Notes

This project shifted my focus from simply writing Arduino code to designing embedded software.

- Interrupts allowed the microcontroller to react immediately to encoder movement instead of continuously polling for changes.
- Separating interrupt-owned variables from application logic made the firmware easier to reason about and debug.
- Breaking the program into dedicated processing functions made the code significantly cleaner than placing everything inside `loop()`.
- I learned that rotary encoders produce four electrical transitions for every physical detent and that software must account for this to achieve stable counting.
- Using a lookup table for PWM levels produced predictable, symmetric speed control while keeping the implementation simple.
- Capturing both encoder signals and PWM output with a logic analyzer reinforced the importance of verifying software with real electrical measurements instead of assuming the code was correct.

⸻

## Long-Term Objective

This project serves as a foundational embedded systems exercise for learning:

* interrupt-driven firmware
* event-driven software architecture
* real-time input processing
* modular embedded programming
* embedded debugging methodology
* hardware signal verification

It also serves as a stepping stone toward more advanced embedded systems development involving timers, communication peripherals, RTOS concepts, and eventually ESP32-based systems.
